metadata.name: The Space Inside #321
metadata.description:
Points fill in shapes on a warped noise field. The resulting images range from soft water colors to distorted, pixelated CRT screens. 

The image is drawn at 3000x3000px and scaled to the browser size. 

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 3000x3000px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Features:
- Two palette sets
- Light or dark background
- 70% color image, 30% monochrome
- Various combinations of circles and rectangles
- All rectangles 
- 7 types of shapes: random circles, packed circles, checkerboard, orbs, ring, spiral, checkerboard and orbs
- Rectangles snap to a grid
- Fuzzy lines connected groups of drawing points
- Fuzzy lines around the dots
- Bright border on the shapes

Rare
- 9% to have a soft monochrome and color palette

No death in the metaverse 
100 billion mortal coils before us, reduced to silly memes 

Here then, a chance to right every wrong 
Or curse ourselves, forgetting we once counted days so keenly

metadata.name: Sand Table #133
metadata.description:
Just like a sand jar that you made or played with as a child. A recreation of layered colored sand with star glitter at the "peaks." Rare versions will be all gold and super rare has rainbow shimmer glitter.

Press 's' to take a screenshot. The image size is 1000x1000. 

Features
- 20 color palettes
- 2 color distribution methods
- 4 sand distribution methods
- sand size variation
- noise variables to determine patterns and layers

Rare features
- color sand with gold stars
- all stars instead of sand grains
- all gold glitter with silver stars
- all rainbow glitter with silver stars (super rare)

metadata.name: sand dunes #5
metadata.description:
A unique pattern is created by adding dots of complementary colors. The dots add up to waves that are narrower and give you the depth of the picture.
Sand dunes or sharp rocks is the first thing I imagine when looking at it.

metadata.name: Zug #86
metadata.description:
Zug is the German word for train, but it also translates to 'a force that pulls in a specific direction' which feels very fitting, though it might remain unclear in which direction exactly.

The image is build layering around 9000 transparent strokes grouped so that the resemblance of a passing train is created. Most strokes are blurred, some are repeating.

All editions share the same base color palette. From it three different palettes are derived for the light, medium and dark colors. Press 'c' to get a better idea of how this works.

Initial sketch made for the Weekly Creative Coding Challenge hosted by Raphaël de Courville (@Sableraph).

Commands:
f = fullscreen toggle
b = change window background color
c = color palettes overlay toggle
s = save image at 1080 x 1920 pixels
p = save image at 3240 x 5760 pixels

metadata.name: Glass is class #230
metadata.description:
Warning: GPU intensive stuff!

may perform badly on lower-end GPUs...

only 512 editions are available, I reserved 512 more just in case some previews don't render correctly...the unminted reserves will be burned.

hold the left mouse button and drag to rotate the view around the center

hover with your mouse to spawn some settings controls:
 - Resolution (performance-heavy)
 - Light bounces
 - Frame Samples
 - Screenshot Button (takes a screenshot...if it doesn't download, you should open the generator in a new tab)

Technique: Pathtracing
Lib: ThreeJS (React Three Fiber)
